article.description: The 2003 edition of the Memphis Grizzlies is starting to look like previous versions.
article.headline: Sonics' Lewis sunk 33 points
article.story: MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- The return of Ray Allen has taken the pressure to carry the Seattle SuperSonics off Rashard Lewis. Lewis scored 33 points and Allen had nine in the final three minutes to lead Seattle to a 105-99 victory over the slumping Memphis Grizzlies on Tuesday night. Lewis and Allen scored Seattle's final 15 points as the Sonics pulled away late. Allen finished with 22 points, playing in his fourth game of the season after a right ankle surgery. "I think we're still trying to find a rhythm together right now. We're just getting the feel of each other," said Lewis, 12-for-18 from the floor with four 3-pointers. "It takes a lot off (me). "It opens up shots for everybody else. Instead of the opposing teams focusing on one person, they have to focus on two, and that's me and Ray on the offensive end." The Grizzlies have lost seven straight, matching their longest losing streak under second-year coach Hubie Brown. "You really can't put a finger on it. When you're winning you play with more confidence. Right now we don't have that swagger like we did. And in a game like tonight, that makes a difference," said Memphis forward Shane Battier, who spent much of the game trying -- unsuccessfully -- to deal with Lewis. Lewis and Allen hit back-to-back 3-pointers to give Seattle an 84-81 lead with 7:50 left. Lewis made it a 9-0 run with a traditional three-point play moments later, going to the hoop and drawing a foul on Battier. Lewis hit another fallaway jumper from the baseline to make it 92-88 with 4:05 left, and Allen scored consecutive fast-break buckets to make it a seven-point game. "Rashard, he's stepped up the last few games and is playing really well," Allen said. "He's hitting his shots in his spots. I have to do a better job right now of getting into the flow of the offense and finding my teammates." Pau Gasol had 32 points and 11 rebounds to lead Memphis, which played without second-leading scorer Bonzi Wells, who was recovering from a concussion he received during Monday's game. Jason Williams had 12 points, 10 in the second half, and seven assists for Memphis. Lewis hit his first seven shots and had 19 points before his first miss in the second quarter. "He got three quick 3s that really started him off. He's a tough cover," Battier said of the 6-foot-10 forward. "I thought I did a decent job of being in his face." The Sonics led by as much as 50-38 in the second half -- but Memphis closed the half with an 6-0 run led by Gasol. He scored 17 points in the first half while the rest of the Memphis starting lineup combined for six. The Grizzlies struggled from the perimeter all night, but 16 offensive rebounds and some good work going to the basket kept them in it. The Sonics had no such troubles from behind the arc, going 11 for 23. "We can't emphasize it any more than before the game and during timeouts that they're going to shoot like this," Brown said. Game Notes: Brown said before the game he was feeling just fine a couple of days after he experienced a few seconds of lightheadedness during a game against Dallas. He checked out OK with doctors. "Everybody knows sometimes you jump up from the couch and you get that. Unfortunately, I got it when cameras were on," Brown said. ... A day after being benched for an entire game for the first time this year, Memphis PG Earl Watson was back as Williams' backup. Wells' injury made the move necessary. ... Brent Barry had 10 points and 10 assists, his first double-double of the season. ... Memphis fell to 10-1 when leading after three quarters.
